description: Proper nouns representing names of people, places, or titles, particularly those associated with Christianity.
Words or parts of words related to travel, voyage, or sailing, and also to the crusades or the Christian cross; prefixes or suffixes indicating extremity, or intensification, or superiority.
Names of significant Christian figures, often referring to Jesus Christ, appearing as standalone proper nouns.
Proper nouns, specifically names, brands, or titles, often abbreviated, and words related to crisis or Christianity.
Proper noun 'Christian' used as a personal name or an adjective referring to the Christian faith.
Names, especially those of Christian origin, are given importance.

Proper nouns often referring to female given names that begin with "Christ", including "Christina", "Christine", "Christiane", "Kristina", and "Kristin", typically being used as personal names in various contexts.
Various forms of the word "pagan", which can be used as a noun or an adjective, referring to pre-Christian, polytheistic cultures or individuals, and their practices.
A title of nobility or respect, often preceding a surname or used as a form of address, commonly associated with British peerage or Christian reverence.
The token appears to be an abbreviation of the word "Father", often used as a title of address for a priest in the Catholic or other Christian traditions.

A descriptive term of a religion or a religious group (mainly "Islamic", but also "Buddhist", "Christian", "Torah", "Muslim", "Hellenic", "Coptic", "Jihad", "Sharia", or "Islamist") is used as an adjective to describe a noun or an institution.

Variations of the word "baptist" or "baptism" across multiple contexts, often referring to the Christian denomination or the act of baptism, as well as unrelated instances of words containing the "bap" or "bapt" sequence.
mentions of the name "Christian."
Titles related to high-ranking Christian clergy, including "Bishop" and "Episcopal", often found in formal or official contexts.
Variations of the words "evangel", "evangelical", "evangelism", and "evangelist", often related to Christian faith and its spread.
References to holidays and celebrations, particularly Christian holidays like Easter, and related concepts such as eggs and bunnies.

The token "apost", "apostle", "apostles", "apostolic" appear to be variations of a root word. This root word is often related to, or found near the word "Epistle". The root word seems to be associated with Christian theology and scripture, often signifying an important figure or writing.
Variations of the words "evangel", "evangelical", "evangelize", and "evangelization", often related to Christian activities or movements.

Words related to Christianity, particularly those describing types of Christian movements or denominations, such as evangelical or pentecostal, as well as words related to Christian concepts and practices.
Names and words related to Christianity, such as "Christ", particularly when used as a proper noun or in a context that suggests religiosity or sanctity.
